<br>
by common sense most people in a classification are average for that classification.  yet most anyone thats been 60 for a month thinks they play their class exceptionally.   I guess thats a game doing its job. games generally make you feel exceptional if you dont dig to deep. <br>
<br>
 something can be learned by considering the specific case of level 60 enchanters.  every level 60 enchanter i ever met thought they were exceptional: gods gift to mezzing.  yet i can tell you cause im not an enchanter having grouped with many that most are adequate and average for a level 60 enchanter.  rarely like 5% of the time i meet a new level 60 enchanter that will impress me.  yet all level 60 enchanters i ever meet think they are impressive.  in reality they are average.  <br>
<br>
BUT this really sheds some light on what we think it means to be a hard class to play.  it has little to do with percentile measurement of skill relative to your peers but instead a hard class is a statement of how much time it takes to get up to speed to be merely adequate.   Specifically again all level 60 enchanters are fairly impressive when compared to their level 40 counter parts.  They have lots of practice and thats the statement of hard  the amount of practice it takes to be adequate.<br>
<br>
<br>
So which classes take the most practice to be adequate groupers?  Difficult to say but some &quot;blocking&quot; is clearly justified.<br>
you can basically block the stun/mez crowd control guys.  bard,chanters, necros as being somewhat equal in difficulty of getting up to speed.<br>
<br>
then you can block the wizard/druids neither of those 2 can get much apart from the other.<br>
<br>
then you can block the spellless rogues/monks/warriors as being roughly equal to get up to speed.<br>
<br>
then you can block the hybrids as having the roughly same need for practice.<br>
<br>
i dont know if its fair to block shamans with mages as a shamans life is much more complicated.  mage pets may do more damage but a shaman still uses a pet and therefor has as much complication as a mage + the whole disease versus magic slow/malo cano/torpor complexity.  it would take a bit longer to get strong with that extra complexity.<br>
<br>
warriors/monks/rogues complexity is domiinated by the momentum. their complexity comes specifically because they have no exceptional options.  in the first 5 seconds you have to figure out how to apply your momentum as you have no way to change it 30 seconds in atleast not instantly.  but all of that really doesnt get noticed cause it actually doesnt take much practice to be adequate.<br>
<br>
edit:<br>
clerics are dominated by attentiveness.  an attentive cleric is usually tagged skillful an unattentive cleric is tagged skillless. a cleric might object that their are big difference in their relative mana efficiencies but this doesnt come under the tag adequate.  its like the little things a rogue with a 130 days played does to make an encounter work: those things go unnoticed by most a subtle secret of the character in question usually passed off as a &quot;good nite.&quot;  as long as a cleric keeps people topped off and chs in time to keep people alive they will look gtg nm the reality.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
